segments.text: All right, boys, thank you a lot, thank you a lot.

Time once again for your old woods rider, Gally Elliot and the Three Knothead.
Friends are sitting here under the big old pine tree.
The pine needed to have fallen, and we're just having a big time.
We're just hoping that you'd pull up a chair and relax there for just a little while.
Because the boys and myself have got a few things here which we just got to tell you.
That's all there is to it.
So stick around.
Relax.
We'll start off here with a good tune.
Features Jack.

Thank you.

And that's what I've been telling you.
Every time we come to you down the air lanes there, I tell you to be careful.
I beg you to be careful with your fire in the woods and your cigarettes and mashes and the woods fires burning off your new grounds and brush heaps and all that sort of stuff.
You know all these things, friends.
I've told them over and over to you.
Of course, you already knew it.
I was just reminding you.
That's all.
And I...
I really hope that you people out there have enjoyed our programs as much as we've enjoyed bringing them to you because we have a swell time.
The boys and myself, we live just the kind of life that you hear on these programs.
We do.
We try to get all out of life we can.
We like the woods.
And I don't believe there's a human being living that don't like to go out in the woods.
I just don't believe there is.
That's a funny thing.
But everybody's got a certain amount of that instinct of some kind.
I don't know.
I guess you'd call it animal instinct or something.
They just love to get out in the woods.
And we've got nice woods.
We've always had nice woods throughout this good old United States in some sections.
And we want to take care of them.
We want them bigger and better.
And God put them here for us to enjoy and use.
And we've got to be careful with them.
We've got to take care of them.

You're driving down the highway.
Put your cigarettes in the ashtray.
Put your matches in the ashtray.
Out in the woods, be sure your matches and cigarettes are dead out before you leave them.
Be careful with your fires and all that sort of stuff.
Well, I've been telling you that every day.
Friends, remember that.

and baby Joe is 10.

Well, now, let's see.
If you girls are about ready there, we'll start.
I think it'd be mighty nice.
to sing a pretty old hymn here for this last program in this series.
Y'all want to do that?
Yes.

Friends, you know...

You know, I just want to right now officially declare war on public enemy number one with us, and that is fire.
Now, we want all of you to join in and help us, friends, and I know you will.
We want to keep these fires out.
I want you to tell folks about it.
You can do your part.
I'll do mine.
We'll all pitch in.
We'll all do our part.
It's just little simple things to do, and you know it as well as I do.
So what do you say we do then?

In other words, help us to cut out these fires.
These unnecessary fires, it costs the government so much.
In the state, everybody loses when we have a wildfire.
Everybody, you and me, our children.
You can't win.
There's not a chance to win.
So if you'll cooperate with us and the average will show it up there in the books and things where we're doing some good, well, then we'll be coming to you more often.
And that'll tickle the boys and myself to death.
And it'll be money in my pocket, your pocket, everybody's pockets.
Don't you see?

Now, they just haven't stopped to realize.
